I have laid out a few simple steps to get me going in the right direction. It is always good to have a plan!

For this example, I am using the **King County House Sales** dataset originally found on Kaggle.



**1. Determine the Objective**
 
> What is the problem I am trying to solve?

I wanted to know which variable most influenced house prices using a statistical model.



**2. Access to Dataset**

> Import "kc_house_data.csv"

Pretty straight forward, import dataset from source (github repo).



**3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)**

> Supervised Learning vs Unsupervised Learning 
 
> Classification vs Regression

>  Prediction vs Inference

Here we need to determine how we collect, sort, and manipulate our data based on our objective.

**Supervised Learning**  -  Computer is learning from our labeled dataset and learning the relationship between our x and y variables. [DV, IV] = [price, sqft]

**Regression**  - Our model contains continouous quantatative variables
 
**Inference** - Determine how he (y) variable is affected by the (x) variable

Then we move on to the fun part.... **data cleaning!** As much fun as having someone breath on you with their mouth...
(Yes now you see how strong visualization can be)

Regardless of the interest, this step is crucial. Bad data can and often is worse than unknown data. So we need to make sure that our data types are as should be. Check missing values (nulls) and determine what you want to do with them. For example, in this dataset there is a field (column) 'sqft_basement' with 424/20107 rows with the attribute '?'. Because those rows of data are meaningless to my objective and account for 21% of the field, I made the executive decision to not use this field at all in my model. After scrubbing the data, I wanted to do a simple visual inspection. So I used a scatterplot and histogram. Scatterplot to check correlation and histogram to check normality.

**4. Baseline Modelling**

> Simple Linear Regression

Now it is time to build the model and test our model. Since we already determined we will use regression, I have chosen to go with **simple linear regression**. The next step is to create a model that can calculate the regression line of each **Predictor** also known as the Independent Variable or x. And then of course, create a plot to visualize the results. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We must also do our due diligence and check our model's statistical summary. Important factors such as R-squared and alpha levels should be noted. We want to make sure our model is both meaningful and not over fitted.
